    { q: "When should a new team member be considered ready to transition from the shadowing period to working with reduced supervision?", options: ["After a fixed number of days regardless of competence demonstrated","When their supervisor confirms they have demonstrated sufficient knowledge and practical skills to work safely with a reduced level of direct oversight","When they request to work independently","After they complete all theoretical training modules in the portal"], correct: 1 },
    { q: "What should happen if, during the shadowing period, a new team member demonstrates unsafe practices?", options: ["Note it in the performance review and address it later","Allow them to continue and correct them at the end of the job","Immediately pause the task, correct the practice with explanation, and re-demonstrate the correct method — extending the shadowing period if necessary","Report it to HR but allow work to continue"], correct: 2 },
    { q: "Which best describes the benefit of the shadowing approach compared to sending a new installer directly to site with instructions?", options: ["Shadowing is faster and cheaper than working directly with guidance on site","Shadowing has no proven benefit over instruction-based training","Observing experienced workers in real conditions builds contextual understanding, correct habits, and practical judgement that cannot be conveyed by written instructions alone","Shadowing is only useful for workers with no prior construction experience"], correct: 3 }
